{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535360"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:54:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:54:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15339"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15339"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.34,0.04,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8030"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61136"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8030"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46583"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"873"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"2443"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44805"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61136"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-week history of worsening headaches and progressive difficulty reading. The headaches are worse in the morning and she inititially thought it was because she lost her reading glasses but it hasn\u0027t improved since buying a replacement set.  She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 138/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals bilateral papilloedema and a right homonymous hemianopia. The remainder of the examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the next best investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Magnetic resonance imaging with contrast","Computed tomography without contrast","Humphrey visual field test","Lumbar puncture","Electroencephalogram"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of raised intracranial pressure (morning headaches, nausea, papilloedema) and focal neurological signs (homonymous hemianopia), raising concern for an intracranial mass lesion such as glioblastoma. Glioblastomas are aggressive with a high morbidity rate, and the cause is unknown.  The majority of glioblastomas occur in the supratentorial region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation as it provides detailed anatomical information about brain lesions, including location, size, extent of oedema, and contrast enhancement patterns. It is particularly useful in distinguishing between different types of brain tumours and planning surgical approaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography without contrast\u003C/strong\u003E would show gross structural abnormalities but lacks the sensitivity and detail of MRI for characterising brain tumours. While it might be performed in emergency situations, MRI with contrast is preferred when available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHumphrey visual field test\u003C/strong\u003E would document the extent of visual field loss but would not identify the underlying cause. While useful for monitoring progression, it should not delay definitive neuroimaging in a patient with papilloedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in this situation as there is evidence of raised intracranial pressure with papilloedema. Performing a lumbar puncture could precipitate herniation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectroencephalogram\u003C/strong\u003E might be useful if seizures were a prominent feature but would not identify the underlying structural lesion. It is not the appropriate first investigation for suspected intracranial tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlioblastoma typically presents with progressive neurological symptoms over weeks to months, usually as the tumour grows leading to necrosis and increased intracrannial pressure or by seizures. The combination of raised intracranial pressure and focal neurological signs should prompt urgent neuroimaging. The presence of papilloedema makes this particularly urgent as it indicates significant mass effect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Progressive visual field defects with headache should raise suspicion for intracranial tumours.","MRI with contrast is the gold standard imaging for suspected glioblastoma."],"references":["Hanif F, Muzaffar K, Perveen K, Malhi SM, Simjee ShU. Glioblastoma Multiforme: A Review of its Epidemiology and Pathogenesis through Clinical Presentation and Treatment. Asian Pac J Cancer Prev. 2017.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5563115/","Xie K, Liu CY, Hasso AN, Crow RW. Visual field changes as an early indicator of glioblastoma multiforme progression: two cases of functional vision changes before MRI detection. Clin Ophthalmol. 2015.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4468993/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46583"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15339"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46583"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T00:49:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T00:50:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8030"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61136"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37: